WEBVTT

00:01.904 --> 00:16.705
If you will, if you'll tell me your full name, for 
starters, and a little about... My name is Alec,

00:01.904 --> 00:16.705
A-L-E-C, Christopher Sears.

00:21.031 --> 00:23.194
And where you were born and raised? Born in 
September 7, 1918, in Abilene, Texas, and grew up

00:23.214 --> 00:31.185
in a town west of there called Merkle, 17 miles.

00:40.105 --> 00:43.529
I went to high school and graduated there. I spent 
two years in McMurray and Abilene. Then I went to

00:53.540 --> 01:00.447
Texas Tech, Lubbock, for a degree in agriculture. 
animal husbandry, minor in economics.

01:09.800 --> 01:30.552
The

01:09.800 --> 01:30.552
succeeding year, I had a graduate fellowship to 
the University of North Dakota at Fargo to work, to

01:09.800 --> 01:30.552
teach, and I'm

01:30.987 --> 01:36.936
going up to Bismarck in June. I'm giving a talk on 
the grasslands. I enjoyed my years up there.

01:44.047 --> 01:56.826
Anyway, I taught half time, went to school half 
time, and earned a master's in animal husbandry

01:44.047 --> 01:56.826
and a minor in economics.

01:59.759 --> 02:04.466
kind of taking off on the education part here. I'll 
go back and pick up my early life.

02:09.213 --> 02:10.816
While we're on it, I might as well finish. While in 
North Dakota, my research project dealt with

02:12.538 --> 02:28.382
vermifuges and parasites in sheep, and I worked 
closely with the veterinary division there in the

02:30.235 --> 02:36.080
school.

02:40.044 --> 02:43.987
I became very interested in veterinary medicine.

02:49.693 --> 02:57.880
This was partially due to my younger brother, two 
years younger, dropped out of Tech and went back

02:58.113 --> 03:07.584
and ran our ranch

02:58.113 --> 03:07.584
at south of Abilene. Constable was married before 
I was, and I felt that the ranch was not large enough

03:09.206 --> 03:21.561
for two people to be managers. So that's the reason 
I went up and got my master's. no thought of it

03:27.914 --> 03:29.896
before that. Had

03:31.357 --> 03:40.846
you started by using your husband's degree for 
county agent work or anything like that? Well, I

03:41.086 --> 03:47.952
had written some letters and I didn't seem very 
excited about what was offered. And this happened

03:48.333 --> 03:50.434
in my senior year. I didn't have a very big gap. They 
had two previous doing the same project with

03:57.007 --> 04:02.734
sheep, something with their sheep. And of course 
Dr. Stangle there at Texas Tech recommended me for

04:04.096 --> 04:20.097
it because I happened to be president of Block 
Bridal Club and I had raised and been on the cattle

04:04.096 --> 04:20.097
rights and sheep rights. When did you finish Tech?

04:27.078 --> 04:27.398
Boy. That's all right. I graduated up from North 
Dakota at 42, and two years there, so that would be

04:29.761 --> 04:39.173
39 to 40. Yeah, just so I can. Yeah.

04:49.946 --> 04:55.313
If you want me to drop back, or I can drop back on my 
childhood earlier, I mean later. Let's go on with

04:58.454 --> 04:59.475
this. The sequence will be better for you, I 
believe. While I was there, of course, the World

05:04.420 --> 05:17.151
War II broke out in December and I graduated in June 
or so of the following year. And I had enlisted in

05:17.171 --> 05:24.017
the Marine Corps during my senior during my second 
year and

05:24.487 --> 05:40.734
had written a thesis, written a paper and a thesis 
and the Marine Corps called me in before

05:24.487 --> 05:40.734
graduation time. The faculty was very 
sympathetic

05:47.200 --> 05:51.705
gave me my exam and accepted this work that I'd 
already done as my thesis. But I'm lucky. You are.

05:57.091 --> 06:16.532
Anyway, I went into the service about March, April 
of 42 and was a, went into the Marine Officer School

05:57.091 --> 06:16.532
and came out a second lieutenant, a Marine, I don't 
think that has a lot to do with veterinary

06:17.474 --> 06:24.004
medicine. I went to Honolulu

06:24.104 --> 06:40.528
and then joined a defense battalion that was in 
Palmyra, one of the islands that was the next one to

06:24.104 --> 06:40.528
be invaded.

06:42.179 --> 06:43.200
I remember not so good. You had a small stroke on . 
Yeah, no, before that. Anyway, before, when we

06:49.647 --> 06:51.610
turned them around. Yeah. was the next . And I was 
there a short while, and then came back and changed

06:55.694 --> 07:05.085
into a field cartel. I had lots of, quite a bit of 
math, and the Marine Corps tried to use your word.

07:12.571 --> 07:15.895
best fitted, and that certainly saved me a lot of 
walking. Vietnam, I'd have been in Vietnam, not

07:16.496 --> 07:20.901
Vietnam, but Guadalcanal. My outfit would have 
gone to Guadalcanal if I'd been in anything but

07:22.203 --> 07:31.274
artillery or coastal artillery. But anyway, I 
came back and then went out to Majuro on a different

07:31.314 --> 07:42.308
outfit. there for a few months, and came, I was 
overseas 23 months, and came back to the United

07:43.047 --> 07:52.720
States. Pacific all the time? Yes, Pacific all the 
time. And went back to Quantico to an advanced

07:56.886 --> 08:05.618
course, and then went back to San Francisco to be 
deployed again. Funny thing that probably the

08:12.089 --> 08:23.241
European war ended while I was going to Quantico, 
and the Japanese war ended while I was on the road to

08:12.089 --> 08:23.241
San Francisco, so I never went back. I was lucky not 
to end up in the occupation.

08:33.152 --> 08:34.673
Okay, from there I... When did you leave service? 
about December 4th, 6th, and I applied for

08:41.468 --> 08:55.282
application to three veterinary schools, 
Cornell and... So you had kind of decided during

08:55.302 --> 08:58.905
the war what you wanted to come back and do. Yes, 
that made up my mind. My brother was running the

09:01.548 --> 09:08.635
ranch until he went into the service, and then of 
course he came back about the same time I did. Went

09:08.655 --> 09:11.037
back to the ranch. So I figured that would be the 
best way to go. Cornell and Colorado and A&M. A&M

09:24.042 --> 09:30.612
accepted more of my previous college work than the 
other two. And therefore, I really would have

09:31.493 --> 09:36.300
liked to have gone to Cornell. But I thought it was a 
better school. It rated better. Yeah, it did. It

09:40.406 --> 09:41.007
was an honor. But that's not for the book. But 
anyway, I went to A&M, the veterinary school, in

09:43.269 --> 10:00.265
January, I believe, mid-semester of 46, and 
graduated in 49. I hit some of the, most of the, I

10:00.465 --> 10:10.335
don't know, three-year schedule at that time.

10:11.362 --> 10:12.924
at least a high sophomore. All my English and most 
of my chemistry and all that was done in history.

10:20.636 --> 10:24.983
But I graduated in 49 from A&M. You were with GI 
Bill. Yes, uh-huh. And I taught in the animal

10:27.167 --> 10:32.695
husbandry.

10:32.715 --> 10:33.757
I was married at that time. I didn't know I asked the 
other. Yeah, I was married and had two children

10:34.939 --> 10:37.723
during that time. So I had to have a little bit more 
than you have to be able to get through. So I taught

10:42.140 --> 11:01.117
in the animal husbandry, mostly

10:42.140 --> 11:01.117
dealing with the judging team, stock doings, and 
telemetry, animal

10:42.140 --> 11:01.117
husbandry. Do you remember anything special 
about any of your professors down there when you

11:01.137 --> 11:06.242
were there, or any special professors? Well, we 
had a few characters, but Dr. Turk was a fellow of

11:07.268 --> 11:14.715
parasitology. My name is Turk. Did you know Tom, my 
name, while you were there? No. What year did he

11:21.922 --> 11:23.544
graduate? About the same time. I was going to look 
at his degree. He was 47. So he's down to 47. I

11:31.952 --> 11:36.516
crisscrossed with some of the 48s, but not 47. 
Anyway, Dr. Turk and, oh, who was the... I think

11:42.599 --> 11:43.920
Marcel is still around. Yes, he was our dean. And 
Dr. Smith. Yeah, he was the head of the physiology

11:50.366 --> 11:54.610
department. I'll think of him in a minute. I have a 
small stroke. a few years back, and I have trouble

12:05.386 --> 12:07.808
on recall. I can think of it. It's fine. But if I try 
to think of it, it just won't come. And the anatomy

12:14.495 --> 12:28.087
teacher, a tall fellow, blond, very 
instrumental. I enjoyed him. Of course, a few of

12:31.230 --> 12:34.093
you didn't enjoy him.

